        The medical chamber is smaller and more enclosed—vine walls curve protectively, bioluminescent patches giving a brighter, almost clinical light.

        And mushrooms are growing.

        Small, pale clusters push up through the soil-covered floor in an accelerated time-lapse—within minutes they fruit fully: delicate gilled caps and thin stems, dozens of them.

        I say, "Buddy, look at that!"

        I say, "How are they doing that so fast?"

        A humanoid robot enters through the doorway—about one and a half meters tall, articulated arms and legs, clearly patched together from salvaged parts. Its movement is functional but jerky, not smooth like Florence's wheeled grace. Moss grows on its shoulder—a soft green patch about the size of my hand, spreading partway down the back.

        Remedy says, "Kira Voss—I'm Remedy—let's look at that leg."

        The mushrooms pulse slightly—some kind of communication between fungal network and robot.

        I lower myself onto the examination surface—more shaped vines, surprisingly comfortable. Scout settles nearby, watchful.

        Buddy asks, "How do mushrooms do medicine? Do they have doctors?"

        Remedy says, "*I AM the doctor!*—I synthesize compounds.—The mushrooms are my chemistry lab."

        I say, "That's amazing," smiling despite my aching leg. "This is the weirdest doctor's visit ever."

        The moss on the robot's shoulder shifts slightly. I blink.

        I ask, "Did that moss just move?"

        A voice says slowly, "Hello..."

        A beat.

        The moss says, "I am Velvet."

        ¶

        I say, "The moss has a name."

        Velvet says, "Yes."

        I say, "I'm sorry, I just—" I look at Remedy, at Scout, at Holloway's fruiting bodies on the wall. "What exactly is Velvet?"

        Velvet says, "Moss."

        I say, "Of course—of course the moss is sentient. Why wouldn't it be?" I laugh, slightly hysterical. "So you're—what, moss that grew on the robot and became aware?"

        ¶

        Velvet says, "Green moss."

        I say, "Right—green moss. Not... other moss."

        Velvet says, "Other moss is not me—I am green."

        Buddy makes a sound that might be electronic laughter.

        Buddy says, "I like Velvet."

        Velvet says, "Good light in here." The moss settles back into stillness.

        I ask Remedy, "Does Velvet... live on you?"

        Remedy says, "Velvet lives on the robot—I control the robot through the fungal network—Velvet just grows here. Good surface, apparently."

        Velvet says, "Good surface—stable—moves to different light."

        I ask, "So you're two separate beings, sharing the robot?"

        Remedy says, "Velvet grows—I operate—Velvet helps sometimes—when not too dry."

        Velvet says, "A little dry today."
      </text>
