        I file this away under "things about this planet I will never fully understand" and refocus on my throbbing leg.

        Holloway flutes, "First, documentation—medical consent forms and allergy verification."

        More forms—but at this point I'm used to them.

        I answer questions—known allergies—Buddy provides my medical file—previous reactions to medications—consent for each compound Remedy plans to synthesize.

        Holloway flutes, "This will take approximately two hours—standard protocol!"

        My leg throbs—the temporary treatment from earlier is wearing off—but watching Remedy work will be interesting.

        The robot moves closer, mechanical hands surprisingly gentle as they examine my leg.

        Remedy says, "Remove the bandage."

        I unwrap the makeshift dressing. The wound beneath looks worse than before—red, swollen, weeping fluid.

        Remedy says, "Bacterial colonization has begun—the proteins are starting to break down—you can see the cellular degradation here." The robot's finger points at the wound edges.

        Remedy says, "Human flesh is approximately sixty percent water, twenty percent protein, fifteen percent fat—very decomposable, actually."

        I say, "Did you just call my leg decomposable?"

        Remedy says, "All organic matter is decomposable—it's just a matter of timing." More mushrooms fruit nearby, different varieties.

        ¶

        Remedy continues, "I could process a whole human body in maybe three weeks—turn it into excellent soil. Not that we're going to—you're alive—but _if_ you died, very efficient decomposition—as a compliment."

        Scout bounces anxiously.

        Buddy considers this. Buddy says, "That's... reassuring? I think?"

        I say, "I'm going with 'reassuring.' Remedy clearly knows their chemistry."

        Remedy says, "*I DO know my chemistry!*—Infection risk is significant, but we'll fix it—antibacterial compounds—anti-inflammatory agents—pain management—wound cleaning—I'll start synthesis now."

        More mushrooms grow—different shapes, sizes, colors. Remedy moves between them, harvesting caps and extracting fluids into salvaged containers.

        Buddy points at a pale orange mushroom and says, "What does that one do?"

        Remedy says, "Antibacterial—breaks down bacterial cell walls. Very effective against the species colonizing Kira's wound."

        Buddy asks, "And the purple one?"

        Remedy says, "Anti-inflammatory—reduces swelling, calms the immune response."

        Buddy says, "This is so cool—can you show us more?"

        Remedy explains each compound as they're synthesized. The robot's obvious expertise is reassuring—they clearly know exactly what they're doing. I watch plant chemistry happen in real time: mushrooms fruiting and being harvested, compounds extracted and tested.

        I say, "Mav never got this kind of medical care—his show had a hospital ship with fancy equipment—this is better, somehow—you're making the medicine right here."

        Remedy says, "Fresh is best—personalized compounds for your specific needs."
      </text>
