        The pain in my leg is getting worse—the temporary treatment has definitely worn off. But I'm fascinated enough that it's still bearable.

        Florence visits briefly—flowers shifting with concern, settling to soft green when she sees the chemistry underway. Scout bounces back and forth between me and Remedy, clearly invested in the process.

        Finally—after what must be two hours but felt shorter because I was watching—Remedy approaches with several prepared compounds.

        Remedy announces:
        "Ready to begin treatment."

        Holloway confirms:
        "All consents documented and filed."

        The robot's hands are surprisingly gentle, cleaning the wound with a solution that stings but feels purposeful. Then antibacterial compounds—cool gel from the extracted mushroom chemistry.

        Remedy says:
        "This will prevent further bacterial decomposition—kills the colonizing species—lets your body's natural processes handle the damaged tissue. Much better than external decomposition."

        I say:
        "You really love talking about decomposition."

        Remedy says:
        "*It's what I do!* — Breaking things down, transforming them into something useful — dead cells become nutrients, nutrients become new growth — it's beautiful, chemically speaking."

        The treatment continues with anti-inflammatory compounds and pain management—warmth spreading through my leg as the sharp edge dulls—more cleaning follows.

        And slowly—wonderfully—the pain begins to recede.

        ¶

        Not gone entirely, but reduced and manageable. The throbbing eases. I can breathe properly again.

        Remedy says with evident satisfaction:
        "The compounds are working—your inflammatory response is decreasing—the bacterial colonization is halted—the wound should heal properly now. Excellent chemistry."

        I say, softly:
        "Thank you."

        I mean it deeply.

        I add:
        "That feels so much better."

        Remedy replies, voice carrying a hint of pleasure:
        "Chemistry works whether you thank it or not—though I am glad you're not decomposing. Much better to have living humans than dead ones."

        Scout bounces approvingly.

        Fresh bandages are applied—soft material from processed plant fibers: clean, sterile, properly secured.

        Remedy says:
        "You'll need to rest now—let the compounds work, let your body heal. I'll fruit antibacterial mushrooms daily for wound care—maybe a week until full recovery."

        I say:
        "Rest sounds wonderful."

        Holloway flutes through the wall fruiting bodies:
        "We've assigned you temporary quarters—Scout will show you the way!"

        Scout bounces toward another doorway immediately.

        I stand. My leg still hurts, but it's bearable now; I can walk without wincing at every step.

        Remedy observes:
        "Human bodies are remarkable—self-healing, adaptive. Much more interesting alive than dead—though both are valid states, chemically."

        I say, smiling:
        "I'll try to stay in the alive state."

        Remedy answers:
        "Excellent plan!"
      </text>
